1. Hardware Layer (Assembly + Firmware)
  a. what it includes
    a. CPU (x86-64, ARM
    b. RAM
    c. Disk controllers
    d. GPUs
    e. Motherboard firmaware(BIOS/UEFI)
  b. languages used
    a. Assembly (critical paths only)
    b. some compiler intrinsics inside C/C++
  c. What windows actually does here
    a. bootstrapping (via bootloader)
    b. Interrupt handling
    c. context switching (CPU state changes)
    d. direct hardware access (through HAL)
  d. Key component
    a. HAL (Hardware Abstraction Layer)
      a. written mostly in C with assembly
      b. hides hardware differences from the kernel
2. Kernel Layer (C, some Assembly)
  a. Key responsibilities
    a. process and thread scheduling
    b. memory management (virtual memory, paging)
    c. interrupt handling
    d. synchronization (locks, semaphores)
3. System Layer (C/C++) - Executive + Drivers
  I. Executive services (Kernel-mode but above core kernel) 
    A. Components
      a. Object Manager
      b. Security Reference Monitor
      c. Process Manager
      d. Plug and Play Manager
      e. Power Manager
  II. Device Drivers
    A. What they do
      a. Interface with hardware(GPU, disk, USB, network)
    B. Types
      a. Kernel-mode drivers(fast, risky)
      b. User-mode drivers(safer, slower)
    c. Languages
      a. C and C++
  III. System Libraries
    * These are critical APIs exposed to applications
      a. ntdll.dll(low-level interface to kernel)
      b. kernel32.dll(core OS functions)
      c. user32.dll (windows system)
      d. gdi32.dll(graphics)
4. Application /UI Layer (C++, C#, others)
  * This is what developers and users interact with.
    A. Native Applications
      a. written in C/C++ 
      b. use Win32 API directly
      c. Examples: system utilities, legacy apps
    B. Managed Applications (.NET)
      a. written in C#
      b. Run on .NET runtime (CLR)
    * What happens under the hood
      - C# - intermediate Language(IL)
      - IL - JIT compiled - machine code
    C. Modern UI Frameworks
      a. WinUI/UWP
      b. WPF (C# + XAML)
How the Layers interact (Real Flow)
  Example: Opening a file
    a. App(C# or C++) calls API (CreateFile)
    b. Win32 API - kernel32.dll
    c. Transition to ntdll.dll
    d. System call into kernel
    e. I/O Manager processess request
    d. Device driver talks to disk
    f. Data returns up the stack


